    "What is an appraisal gap and how do I handle one?",
    "An appraisal gap occurs when the purchase price agreed to by buyer and seller exceeds the appraised value — meaning the lender won't finance the full purchase price. Example: You offered $425,000, the appraisal comes in at $410,000. The lender will only finance up to $410,000. You now have a $15,000 gap to address. **Your options**: (1) Renegotiate with the seller: The most common resolution — seller agrees to reduce the price to $410,000 (or meets somewhere in between). Most sellers prefer this to losing the deal. (2) Pay the gap in cash: If you have savings, you can pay $15,000 extra out of pocket at closing (lender still loans on $410K, you pay the $15K gap). (3) Challenge the appraisal: Submit a 'Reconsideration of Value' with 3 comparable sales the appraiser missed. Appraisers are sometimes wrong. (4) Exercise your appraisal contingency: If you have one, terminate and get earnest money back. **Appraisal gap coverage clause**: When you're in a competitive market and know you might pay above appraised value, include an 'appraisal gap coverage' clause in your offer: 'Buyer will pay up to $X above appraised value.' This prevents the appraisal contingency from killing the deal."
