    "How do seller-paid mortgage rate buydowns work?",
    "A seller-paid rate buydown (often called a 'seller credit to buy down the rate') is an increasingly popular negotiating tool in 2025-2026 where the seller pays a lump sum to reduce the buyer's mortgage interest rate. Two common types: **Permanent buydown**: Seller pays 'points' to permanently reduce the interest rate. 1 point = 1% of the loan amount, typically reduces the rate by 0.25%. Example: On a $320,000 loan, buying down 0.5% (2 points = $6,400) saves the buyer ~$105/month for 30 years = $37,800 total interest savings. **Temporary buydown (2-1 buydown)**: Seller pays a lump sum to reduce the rate by 2% in year 1 and 1% in year 2, then regular rate in year 3+. Example: Rate of 7% becomes 5% year 1, 6% year 2, 7% year 3+. This reduces the initial monthly payment, helping buyers qualify and afford the early years of homeownership. **When to negotiate for a buydown**: Instead of a price reduction. In a higher-rate environment where payment affordability is the constraint. When the seller is motivated but reluctant to drop price (preserves their comp). **The math matters**: Compare the monthly savings of a rate buydown vs. a straight price reduction — they're not always equivalent in value to you."
