    "What is PMI and how do I avoid it?",
    "PMI (Private Mortgage Insurance) is insurance that protects the lender (not you) if you default on a conventional loan with less than 20% down. You pay for it; it benefits the lender. PMI cost: typically 0.5-1.5% of the loan amount per year. On a $320,000 loan, that's $1,600-$4,800/year ($133-$400/month). How to avoid PMI: (1) Put 20% down — the simplest way. (2) Piggyback loan (80-10-10): take a first mortgage for 80%, second mortgage for 10%, and put 10% down. No PMI on the first, but second mortgage has a higher rate. (3) Lender-paid PMI (LPMI): lender pays the PMI but charges a slightly higher interest rate. Works best if you plan to sell within 5-7 years (rate is permanent but PMI would have been removed from standard PMI). (4) VA loan: no PMI at all. (5) Some community banks offer portfolio loans with no PMI at higher rates. Removing PMI: For conventional loans, you can request PMI removal when you reach 20% equity (based on original purchase price). Lender must automatically terminate at 22% equity. You can also request removal early if home value has increased significantly and you have 20% equity based on a new appraisal."
