    "What is a good faith estimate vs. a loan estimate?",
    "Good faith estimates (GFEs) are the old format — they were replaced by the Loan Estimate (LE) in 2015 under the TRID (TILA-RESPA Integrated Disclosure) regulations. If someone mentions a 'good faith estimate' today, they're referring to what is now officially called the Loan Estimate. Here's what changed: **Old Good Faith Estimate**: Used pre-2015. Less standardized format. Allowed more variation between the estimate and final closing costs. **Current Loan Estimate**: Standardized 3-page form required for all residential mortgages. Must be provided within 3 business days of application. Lenders are legally bound to the accuracy of the LE — significant variances at closing (beyond tolerances) must be remedied. Makes comparison shopping much easier. Certain fees can only increase within specified tolerances: Section A fees (origination): Cannot increase. Section B fees (lender-required services): Cannot increase. Transfer taxes: Cannot increase. Section C services (you can shop): Can vary. Escrow/prepaid: Can vary by 10% tolerance. **The practical result**: You can now take multiple Loan Estimates from different lenders and compare them directly — fee by fee. This is the most important reason to shop multiple lenders."
